.TH BUNPY-PM-CONFIG 1 "2026-04-27" "bunpy" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
bunpy-pm-config \- print parsed pyproject.toml as JSON
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bunpy pm config
.RI [ path ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Reads
.I pyproject.toml
(default
.IR ./pyproject.toml ),
parses it as a PEP 621
.B [project]
table plus an optional
.B [tool.bunpy]
table, and prints a JSON object to stdout.
.PP
The output has three top-level keys:
.TP
.B project
PEP 621 fields: name, version, dependencies, optional-dependencies,
authors, maintainers, license, readme, scripts, gui-scripts,
entry-points, urls, keywords, classifiers, dynamic.
.TP
.B tool
The
.B [tool.bunpy]
table, kept verbatim. Empty when not set.
.TP
.B other
Any unrecognised top-level table (for example
.BR [build-system] )
preserved verbatim so callers do not lose fidelity.
.SH STRICT MODE
.B bunpy pm config
runs in strict mode and rejects:
.IP \[bu] 2
A missing
.B [project]
table.
.IP \[bu] 2
A missing or empty
.BR project.name .
.IP \[bu] 2
A
.B project.name
that does not match the PEP 503 regex
.RB ( ^[A-Za-z0-9]([A-Za-z0-9._-]*[A-Za-z0-9])?$ ).
.IP \[bu] 2
A
.B project.dynamic
entry that is also set literally (PEP 621 \(sc5.4).
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero on a successful parse. Non-zero on a missing file, a TOML
syntax error, or any of the validation failures above.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bunpy-pm (1),
.BR bunpy (1).
